Air is all around us. We cannot see or touch but can feel it. It has no smell but has 
weigh t and occupies space. All living things need air to breathe. Moving air is called

Air is a mixtur e of different gases, dust particles, water vapour and smok e. The 
main gases presen t in the air are oxygen, nitrogen and carbon dioxide. Oxygen is 
import ant for all living beings. We breathe in oxygen and breathe out carbon 
dioxide. Plan ts take in this carbon dioxide to prepar e their food and give out 
oxygen. In this way, balance of oxygen and carbon dioxide are main tained in the air.Components of Air
Other uses of air
! The tyres of vehicles have air filled in them.
! Air is used to dry clothes.
! Sailboa ts in the water move with the help of air.
! Air is needed for burning.
! We blow up balloons and fly kites with the help of air.
Air P ollution
We need fresh air to breathe. Dust particles, 
smoke and poisonous gases coming from 
vehicles and factories mak e the air harm ful to 
health. It is called polluted air. Polluted air 
causes man y health problems. So, we mus t keep 
the air clean.

How to k eep the air clean?
Governmen t has made some laws to check air pollution but is it not sufficien t. 
Some ways by which we can help to decr ease air pollution are–
! Get your vehicle's pollution check ed from time to time.
! Avoid burning coal and wood.
! Plan t more and more trees because trees help to clean the air.
Let us try our best to keep the air clean so that we do not fall sick.
Just like air, water is very import ant for living beings. All plan ts and animals need 
water to live. We need water in man y activities like drinking , washing , cleaning , 
cooking , bathing etc. Plan ts can not grow without water.Water
Drinking Washing Cooking Bathing
Rain is the main sour ce of w ater. Rain water fills up lak es, riv ers and ponds. Some 
rainwater goes under the surface of the earth. This water is taken out through 
wells, tube wells etc. This is called ground water.Sources of W ater
River Pond Well TubewellWatering plants
Environmental Studies-3 96

Water that we get from ponds, lakes and rivers is not fit for drinking. It contains dirt 
and germs. Waste from factories and homes is released into the rivers. Other 
human activities like washing clothes, bathing animals and throwing garbag e into 
the water sour ces also mak es water dirty . It is called water pollution. Consump tion 
of pollut ed water causes man y diseases such as choler a, jaundice, diarrhoea  and 
typhoid. So, water mus t be cleaned before we consume it. At homes, water filter or 
water purifier is fitted to mak e water fit for drinking. In cities, the cleaning of water 
is done in Water Works.Clean water for drinkingRiver water flows into the sea. Ther e is a lot of water in seas and oceans but it is 
salty . We cannot drink it.
March 22 is celebrated as World Water Day every year.
Water is very precious for us. In some places it is not available throughout the year. 
So, we mus t not pollut e and waste water. We should conser ve water to mak e it 
available for the futur e gener ations too.Water is precious
Gener ally, rainwater flows out to drains 
and is not put to any use. We can collect 
this water and make it useful. 
Rain water harvesting is the process to 
collect rainwater in deep holes in the 
ground. Rain water can also be collect ed 
in tanks and used for watering plan ts or 
cleaning the house.Rainwater harvesting

Rain is the main sour ce of water on earth. But, how do we get rain?
The water in rivers, lakes, seas etc. gets heated up by the sun and chang es into 
water vapour . Water vapour rises up in 
the sky, becomes cool and forms tiny 
drople ts of water. These tiny drople ts 
join together and form clouds. When the 
clouds become very heavy, the water 
falls down on earth as rain. This rain 
water flows back into the rivers, lakes, 
seas etc. Then, it goes up again as water 
vapour and the cycle continues. The 
process of water changing into water 
vapour and then back into water is called the water cycle.Water Cycle

The sun, the moon and the stars that we see in the sky are called heavenly 
bodies. The sky is a vast emp ty space. Wher e we see heavenly bodies space 
including heavenly bodies is called  univ erse. Thus, the sun, moon, stars 
plane ts etc. are a part of univ erse.! Can y ou name the giv en pictur es?
! Wher e do y ou see the sun, moon and s tars?StarterLook a t the giv en pictur es.
Plane ts– Heavenly bodies that revolve around the sun are called plane ts. Our earth 
is a plane t.
Solar System–  The sun and the plane ts moving around it form a family called solar 
system. 
Ther e are eigh t plane ts in our solar system:
Mercury, Venus, Earth, Mass, Jupit er, Saturn, Uranus and Neptune.The Solar System
Let’sKNOW Let’sKNOW
Environmental Studies-3101

All these plane ts move around the sun on their fixed paths called orbits.
Plane ts do not have their own light. They reflect the light of the sun.
Jupiter is the biggest planet of our solar system.
We live on earth. The Earth is the third plane t from the sun in the solar system. It is 
consider ed a unique plane t because it has life due to the presence of air and water 
on it. The Earth
Shape of the Earth
The earth seems to be flat , but actually it is round like an 
orange and sligh tly flat at the poles. 
Atmosphere onEarth-  The earth is surrounded by a blanket of air called 
atmospher e. All living beings need air to live. Air is a mixtur e of man y gases, tiny 
dust particles and water vapour . It is tasteless, colourless and invisible.
Water on E arth–  Nearly thr ee-fourth (71%) of the E arth's surf ace is c overed with 
water. This water is in the form of glacier s, oceans, river, lakes, etc. We cannot live 
without water.
Movements of the Earth
The Earth is moving all the time. It shows two types of movemen ts: rotation and 
revolutionYou  Know Must (Knowledge )
Environmental Studies-3 102

1. Rotation– The Earth spins like a top all the time. It spins around an imaginar y 
line form North pole to South pole. This imaginar y line is called axis. The 
spinning of the earth on its own axis is called rotation.
 The earth takes 24 hour s to comple te one rotation.
The earth spins fr om west to east. Days and nigh ts are formed due to the rotation of the earth.
2. Revolution– The movement of the earth 
around the sun is called revolution. While 
rotating on its axis, the earth also goes 
around the sun.
 Earth takes 365¼ days to complete one 
revolution. The revolution of the earth causes 
chang e of seasons.
The heavenly bodies, which revolve around the 
plane ts are called satellites. The Earth has only one 
natural satellite. We call it the Moon. The Moon 
moves around the Earth.  It does not have its own 
light. It shines because it reflects the light of the sun 
falling on it. The Moon takes about 27.3 days  to 
complete its one revolution around the Earth. The Moon
Ther e is no air on the moon, so life is not possible on it.  The first man who landed 
on the moon was Neil Arms trong.You  Know Must (Knowledge )

Gener ally we indic ate the location of a person, place or thing by using words 
such as right, left, front, behind etc. But these words are not always effectiv e 
as your 'left' will be 'righ t' to other person coming towards you.
To avoid such confusion, we use four main directions. These are East, West, 
North and South. The rising and setting of sun help s us to know the directions. 
If you stand facing the rising sun, you are facing the East. West is at your back. 
Left of you is North and right of you is South.
Ther e are four sub-dir ections also. They are: north-eas t, north-w est, south-
east and south-w est.! If you stand in y our assembly gr ound f acing the rising sun, do y ou kno w

A map is the drawing of a place made after 
actual measur emen ts. It is always drawn 
on a flat surface. The top of the map 
always shows north. A map can be of a 
country, city, town or the entire world. A 
book of map s is called an atlas.Map
Map s are very useful to us.
! They help us to find out the location of a place easily .
! They save our time in locating and reaching our target place.
! Map s are useful for pilots and sailor s. They can keep track of their position in the 
air and in the water by looking at map s.Uses of mapsOceans & continents
The art of drawing maps is called cartogr aphy. The person who 
draws maps is called a cartogr apher .
While drawing a map, we use certain pictur es and signs to represen t different 
features. They are called symbols. Symbols are used to show various structur es 
such as railway lines, rivers, temples, power stations, airports etc. on a map.Symbols in a map
